                                        <h3 id="kicker" class="kicker" role="kicker">
                                                                                            <span class="kicker-label"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20180316023154/https://www.nytimes.com/pages/nyregion/index.html">N.Y. / Region</a></span>
                                                                                                                                                                    </h3>
                        			<h1 itemprop="headline" id="headline" class="headline">Milton Brumer, 97, Engineer For Famed New York Bridges</h1>
	                                                <div id="story-meta-footer" class="story-meta-footer">
                                                                                                    

<p class="byline-dateline"><span class="byline" itemprop="author creator" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">By <span class="byline-author" data-byline-name="NICK RAVO" itemprop="name">NICK RAVO</span></span><time class="dateline" datetime="1999-08-10T01:00:00-04:00" itemprop="dateModified" content="1999-08-10T01:00:00-04:00">AUG. 10, 1999</time>
</p>

                                    <div class="story-meta-footer-sharetools">
                        <div id="sharetools-story-meta-footer" aria-label="tools" role="group" class="sharetools theme-classic  sharetools-story-meta-footer  " data-shares="facebook,twitter,email,show-all,save" data-url="https://web.archive.org/web/20180316023154oe_/https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/10/nyregion/milton-brumer-97-engineer-for-famed-new-york-bridges.html" data-title="Milton Brumer, 97, Engineer For Famed New York Bridges" data-author="By NICK RAVO" data-media="" data-description="Milton Brumer, engineer who managed construction of such mighty bridges as Verrazano-Narrows over New York Bay, Throgs Neck over East River, and Walt Whitman over Delaware, dies at age 97 (M)" data-publish-date="August 10, 1999">
<a class="visually-hidden skip-to-text-link" href="#story-continues-1">Continue reading the main story</a>
<span class="sharetools-label visually-hidden">Share This Page</span>
<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad hidden nocontent robots-nocontent">
<a class="visually-hidden skip-to-text-link" href="#story-continues-1">Continue reading the main story</a>
</div>
</div><!-- close shareTools -->
                                                                                                </div>
                            </div><!-- close story-meta-footer -->
        </div><!-- close story-meta -->
    </header>

    

        
    <div class="story-body-supplemental">
    <div class="story-body story-body-1">
        <p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="282" data-total-count="282">Milton Brumer, an engineer who managed the construction of such mighty bridges as the Verrazano-Narrows over New York Bay, the Throgs Neck over the East River, and the Walt Whitman over the Delaware, died Thursday at a hospital in Boca Raton, Fla. He was 97 and lived in Boca Raton.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="484" data-total-count="766">In a career that spanned half a century, Mr. Brumer had prime responsibility for major engineering projects all over the world. He supervised construction of portions of the Garden State Parkway, the New Jersey Turnpike, the Connecticut Turnpike, the Long Island Expressway,  the Palisades Interstate Parkway in New York and New Jersey and the Ohio Turnpike. He was the engineer in charge of numerous bridges of reinforced concrete and steel for the Victoria Mines Railroad in Brazil.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="149" data-total-count="915">He brought his expertise to projects like the Outerbridge Crossing, Goethals Bridge, George Washington Bridge, Bayonne Bridge and the Lincoln Tunnel.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="186" data-total-count="1101">Mr. Brumer started his career as an assistant engineer in 1923 with the Interborough Rapid Transit Company and later worked for the Pennsylvania Turnpike Commission as a tunnel designer.</p><div id="story-ad-1" class="story-ad ad ad-placeholder nocontent robots-nocontent ">
    <div class="accessibility-ad-header visually-hidden">
    <p>Advertisement</p>
</div>
<a class="visually-hidden skip-to-text-link" href="#story-continues-1">Continue reading the main story</a>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="289" data-total-count="1390" id="story-continues-1">In 1940, Mr. Brumer joined the engineering consulting firm of O. H. Ammann, the firm of Othmar H. Ammann, the fabled builder of the George Washington Bridge, the Triborough Bridge and other projects. By 1949, he had become a partner in the firm, which was then known as Ammann and Whitney.</p><div class="newsletter-signup hidden auto-newsletter variant-1-hidden " id="newsletter-promo" data-newsletter-productcode="" data-newsletter-producttitle="" aria-labeledby="newsletter-promo-heading">
    <h2 class="visually-hidden" id="newsletter-promo-heading">Newsletter Sign Up</h2>
    <a class="visually-hidden skip-to-text-link" href="#continues-post-newsletter">Continue reading the main story</a>
        
